<emphasis id="3285EAA6FFEF8A09F4CFF09DF4A7D600" bold="true" box="[2819,2850,3900,3939]" pageId="32" pageNumber="311">Is</emphasis>
(Iriomotejima and Kohamajima), Ryukyu 
<emphasis id="3285EAA6FFEF8A09F839F0D1F799D6F4" bold="true" box="[2037,2076,3952,3991]" pageId="32" pageNumber="311">Is.</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="48EB653FFFEF8A08F891F005FBA4DAF2" lastPageId="33" lastPageNumber="312" pageId="32" pageNumber="311" type="description">
<paragraph id="004E36B4FFEF8A08F891F005FBA4DAF2" blockId="32.[1885,3509,3372,4627]" lastBlockId="33.[195,1819,342,2345]" lastPageId="33" lastPageNumber="312" pageId="32" pageNumber="311">
<emphasis id="3285EAA6FFEF8A09F891F005F731D6A8" bold="true" box="[1885,2228,4004,4043]" pageId="32" pageNumber="311">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 39-47- 
<quantity id="C7099B51FFEF8A09F5FEF005F522D6A8" box="[2610,2727,4004,4043]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="32" pageNumber="311" unit="mm" value="8.0">8 mm</quantity>
, tail 18-1-26- 
<quantity id="C7099B51FFEF8A09F47FF005F3A3D6A8" box="[2995,3110,4004,4043]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="32" pageNumber="311" unit="mm" value="1.0">1 mm</quantity>
, ear 17-9-18- 
<quantity id="C7099B51FFEF8A09F2E3F005F22DD6A8" box="[3375,3496,4004,4043]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" pageId="32" pageNumber="311" unit="mm" value="9.0">9 mm</quantity>
, hindfoot 8- 
<quantity id="C7099B51FFEF8A09F7FEF07BF752C962" box="[2098,2263,4058,4097]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.5" metricValueMax="9.0" metricValueMin="4.0" pageId="32" pageNumber="311" unit="mm" value="6.5" valueMax="9.0" valueMin="4.0">4â€”9 mm</quantity>
, forearm 40- 
<quantity id="C7099B51FFEF8A09F61DF07BF50DC962" box="[2513,2696,4058,4097]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.3" metricValueMax="4.3" metricValueMin="0.3" pageId="32" pageNumber="311" unit="mm" value="23.0" valueMax="43.0" valueMin="3.0">3â€”43 mm</quantity>
. The 
<emphasis id="3285EAA6FFEF8A09F539F07BF419C962" box="[2805,2972,4058,4097]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="311">Yaeyama</emphasis>
Horseshoe Bat is similar to the Littlejapanese Horseshoe 
<emphasis id="3285EAA6FFEF8A09F655EFAFF65FC956" bold="true" box="[2457,2522,4110,4149]" pageId="32" pageNumber="311">Bat</emphasis>
(. 
<emphasis id="3285EAA6FFEF8A09F5E5EFAFF55CC956" box="[2601,2777,4110,4149]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="311">
<taxonomicName id="C7F14D37FFEF8A09F5E5EFAFF538C956" authorityName="Temminck" authorityYear="1834" box="[2601,2749,4110,4149]" class="Mammalia" family="Rhinolophidae" genus="Rhinolophus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="32" pageNumber="311" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cornutus">cornutus</taxonomicName>
).
</emphasis>
Subspecies 
<taxonomicName id="C7F14D37FFEF8A09F471EFAFF3E8C956" authorityName="Hill &amp; Yoshiyuki" authorityYear="1980" box="[3005,3181,4110,4149]" class="Mammalia" family="Rhinolophidae" genus="Rhinolophus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="32" pageNumber="311" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="imaizumii">
<emphasis id="3285EAA6FFEF8A09F471EFAFF3E8C956" box="[3005,3181,4110,4149]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="311">imaizumii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is larger than 
<taxonomicName id="C7F14D37FFEF8A09F2BDEFAFF833C908" authorityName="K. Andersen" authorityYear="1918" class="Mammalia" family="Rhinolophidae" genus="Rhinolophus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="32" pageNumber="311" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="perditus">
<emphasis id="3285EAA6FFEF8A09F2BDEFAFF833C908" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="311">perditus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the two taxa do not overlap in craniodental morphometries. Pelage is woolly and glossy, dorsal pelage being bright brown (base of hairs light beige), ventral pelage similar 
<emphasis id="3285EAA6FFEF8A09F82BEF0CF7AFC9B7" box="[2023,2090,4269,4308]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="311">but</emphasis>
paler and creamier brown. Ears are moderate-sized. Noseleaf has a slightly concave-sided lancet; connecting process is hom-like, curved anteriorly, narrow, and slender; sella has a broad base with a slightly constricted center and a rounded, anteriorly deflected tip; horseshoe is 
<emphasis id="3285EAA6FFEF8A09F609EEEDF58DC810" box="[2501,2568,4428,4467]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="311">not</emphasis>
very broad (7- 
<quantity id="C7099B51FFEF8A09F4D7EEEDF415C810" box="[2843,2960,4428,4467]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="32" pageNumber="311" unit="mm" value="3.0">3 mm</quantity>
), with no lateral leaflets, and a short, narrow median emargination. Lower lip has three mental grooves. Baculum is 4-2-4- 
<quantity id="C7099B51FFEF8A09F81EEE17F7C5C8BE" box="[2002,2112,4534,4573]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="32" pageNumber="311" unit="mm" value="4.0">4 mm</quantity>
long and has a very deep dorsal notch on the basal cone 
<emphasis id="3285EAA6FFEF8A09F3B4EE17F34CC8BE" bold="true" box="[3192,3273,4534,4573]" pageId="32" pageNumber="311">with</emphasis>
a small ventral notch; shaft is nearly cylindrical and is bent on the distal one-half. 
<emphasis id="3285EAA6FFEF8A09F350EE4DF37ECB70" bold="true" box="[3228,3323,4588,4627]" pageId="32" pageNumber="311">Skull</emphasis>
is similar to that of the LittleJapanese Horseshoe Bat but can be distinguished based on craniodental measurements; skull is long and narrow, and zygomatic width is slighdy greater than 
<emphasis id="3285EAA6FFEE8A08FEFFFE60FE78D88B" box="[307,509,449,488]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="312">
(
<taxonomicName id="C7F14D37FFEE8A08FE8CFE60FE75D88B" authorityName="Hill &amp; Yoshiyuki" authorityYear="1980" box="[320,496,449,488]" class="Mammalia" family="Rhinolophidae" genus="Rhinolophus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="33" pageNumber="312" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="imaizumii">imaizumii</taxonomicName>
)
</emphasis>
or subequal to 
<emphasis id="3285EAA6FFEE8A08FC8EFE60FC60D88B" box="[834,997,449,488]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="312">
(
<taxonomicName id="C7F14D37FFEE8A08FC82FE60FC5CD88B" authorityName="K. Andersen" authorityYear="1918" box="[846,985,449,488]" class="Mammalia" family="Rhinolophidae" genus="Rhinolophus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="33" pageNumber="312" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="perditus">perditus</taxonomicName>
)
</emphasis>
mastoid width; anterior median swellings are small and subcircular; posterior compartments are moderate in size; rostral profile slopes 
<emphasis id="3285EAA6FFEE8A08FE5AFD8AFDE1DB31" box="[406,612,555,594]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="312">posteriorly</emphasis>
; sagittal crest is 
<emphasis id="3285EAA6FFEE8A08FC6AFD8AFBA1DB31" box="[934,1060,555,594]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="312">weakly</emphasis>
to moderately developed; supraorbital crests are weak; frontal depression is shallow. Dental distinctions between subspecies are small but present; 
<taxonomicName id="C7F14D37FFEE8A08FDA4FD34FC90DBDF" authorityName="Hill &amp; Yoshiyuki" authorityYear="1980" box="[616,789,661,700]" class="Mammalia" family="Rhinolophidae" genus="Rhinolophus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="33" pageNumber="312" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="imaizumii">
<emphasis id="3285EAA6FFEE8A08FDA4FD34FC90DBDF" box="[616,789,661,700]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="312">imaizumii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a higher crown portion of C1 compared to 
<emphasis id="3285EAA6FFEE8A08F94AFD34F893DBDF" box="[1670,1814,661,700]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="312">
<taxonomicName id="C7F14D37FFEE8A08F94AFD34F895DBDF" authorityName="K. Andersen" authorityYear="1918" box="[1670,1808,661,700]" class="Mammalia" family="Rhinolophidae" genus="Rhinolophus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="33" pageNumber="312" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="perditus">perditus</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
this being comparatively stout in 
<emphasis id="3285EAA6FFEE8A08FCFAFD6AFC4DDB91" box="[822,968,715,754]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="312">
<taxonomicName id="C7F14D37FFEE8A08FCFAFD6AFC47DB91" authorityName="K. Andersen" authorityYear="1918" box="[822,962,715,754]" class="Mammalia" family="Rhinolophidae" genus="Rhinolophus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="33" pageNumber="312" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="perditus">perditus</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
C-M3 tooth row is slightly shorter in 
<taxonomicName id="C7F14D37FFEE8A08F95CFD6AF89EDB91" authorityName="K. Andersen" authorityYear="1918" box="[1680,1819,715,754]" class="Mammalia" family="Rhinolophidae" genus="Rhinolophus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="33" pageNumber="312" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="perditus">
<emphasis id="3285EAA6FFEE8A08F95CFD6AF89EDB91" box="[1680,1819,715,754]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="312">perditus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but zygomatic width is greater than in 
<emphasis id="3285EAA6FFEE8A08FC6CFD5FFBD1DA46" box="[928,1108,766,805]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="312">
<taxonomicName id="C7F14D37FFEE8A08FC6CFD5FFBCFDA46" authorityName="Hill &amp; Yoshiyuki" authorityYear="1980" box="[928,1098,766,805]" class="Mammalia" family="Rhinolophidae" genus="Rhinolophus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="33" pageNumber="312" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="imaizumii">imaizumii</taxonomicName>
;
</emphasis>
P2 and P3 are within the tooth row in 
<taxonomicName id="C7F14D37FFEE8A08FF08FC94FECADA3F" authorityName="K. Andersen" authorityYear="1918" box="[196,335,821,860]" class="Mammalia" family="Rhinolophidae" genus="Rhinolophus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="33" pageNumber="312" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="perditus">
<emphasis id="3285EAA6FFEE8A08FF08FC94FECADA3F" box="[196,335,821,860]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="312">perditus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but both are extruded from the tooth 
<emphasis id="3285EAA6FFEE8A08FB9FFC94FB1FDA3F" box="[1107,1178,821,860]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="312">row</emphasis>
internally in 
<emphasis id="3285EAA6FFEE8A08FA64FC94F9DEDA3F" box="[1448,1627,821,860]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="312">
<taxonomicName id="C7F14D37FFEE8A08FA64FC94F9D3DA3F" authorityName="Hill &amp; Yoshiyuki" authorityYear="1980" box="[1448,1622,821,860]" class="Mammalia" family="Rhinolophidae" genus="Rhinolophus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="33" pageNumber="312" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="imaizumii">imaizumii</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Chromosomal complement has 2n = 62 and FNa = 60.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="48EB653FFFEE8A08FF09FC3EFDEEDE2E" pageId="33" pageNumber="312" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="004E36B4FFEE8A08FF09FC3EFD30DAA5" blockId="33.[195,1819,342,2345]" box="[197,693,927,966]" pageId="33" pageNumber="312">Habitat. Forested habitats.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="004E36B4FFEE8A08FF09FC75FE6CDC67" blockId="33.[195,1819,342,2345]" pageId="33" pageNumber="312">
<emphasis id="3285EAA6FFEE8A08FF09FC75FEF8DA98" bold="true" box="[197,381,980,1019]" pageId="33" pageNumber="312">Food and</emphasis>
Feeding. The 
<emphasis id="3285EAA6FFEE8A08FD59FC75FCB9DA98" box="[661,828,980,1019]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="312">Yaeyama</emphasis>
Horseshoe Bat feeds on arthropods. Study of wing morphology showed that the species is suspected to forage in cluttered spaces. It has been recorded feeding largely on 
<taxonomicName id="C7F14D37FFEE8A08FC96FB9FFAB2DD06" authority=", Coleoptera" authorityName="Coleoptera" box="[858,1335,1086,1125]" class="Insecta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="33" pageNumber="312" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Lepidoptera, Coleoptera</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="C7F14D37FFEE8A08FA83FB9FF9DCDD06" box="[1359,1625,1086,1125]" class="Insecta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="33" pageNumber="312" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Hymenoptera</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="C7F14D37FFEE8A08F905FB9FFE97DDF9" class="Insecta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="33" pageNumber="312" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Diptera</taxonomicName>
, although it also 
<emphasis id="3285EAA6FFEE8A08FD82FBD2FCB7DDF9" box="[590,818,1139,1178]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="312">occasionally</emphasis>
takes 
<taxonomicName id="C7F14D37FFEE8A08FC6FFBD2F9EDDDF9" authority=", Neuroptera, Trichoptera" authorityName="Neuroptera, Trichoptera" box="[931,1640,1139,1178]" class="Insecta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="33" pageNumber="312" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Orthoptera, Neuroptera, Trichoptera</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="C7F14D37FFEE8A08F905FBD2FEA6DDAC" authorityName="Clerck" authorityYear="1757" class="Arachnida" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="33" pageNumber="312" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Araneae</taxonomicName>
. Presence of 
<taxonomicName id="C7F14D37FFEE8A08FDEEFB09FD46DDAC" authorityName="Clerck" authorityYear="1757" box="[546,707,1192,1231]" class="Arachnida" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="33" pageNumber="312" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Araneae</taxonomicName>
in the diet indicates that the species probably also gleans prey off foliage.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="004E36B4FFEE8A08FF0AFAB3F948DC0C" blockId="33.[195,1819,342,2345]" pageId="33" pageNumber="312">
Breeding. The 
<emphasis id="3285EAA6FFEE8A08FE15FAB3FD05DC5A" box="[473,640,1298,1337]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="312">Yaeyama</emphasis>
Horseshoe 
<emphasis id="3285EAA6FFEE8A08FC93FAB3FC1ADC5A" bold="true" box="[863,927,1298,1337]" pageId="33" pageNumber="312">Bat</emphasis>
exhibits restricted seasonal monoestry; females form maternity colonies in May, and give birth to a single young around this time.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="004E36B4FFEE8A08FF0FFADCFCA9DF1B" blockId="33.[195,1819,342,2345]" pageId="33" pageNumber="312">
<emphasis id="3285EAA6FFEE8A08FF0FFADCFD81DCC7" bold="true" box="[195,516,1405,1444]" pageId="33" pageNumber="312">Activity patterns.</emphasis>
Yaeyama Horseshoe Bats are 
<emphasis id="3285EAA6FFEE8A08FB87FADCFB33DCC7" box="[1099,1206,1405,1444]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="312">active</emphasis>
throughout the year, but probably hibernate through the winter with regular bouts of arousal to forage. 
<emphasis id="3285EAA6FFEE8A08F980FA13F928DCBA" box="[1612,1709,1458,1497]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="312">They</emphasis>
roost in caves, abandoned mines, and bomb shelters during the day and forage 
<emphasis id="3285EAA6FFEE8A08F9A1FA46F91CDF6D" box="[1645,1689,1511,1550]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="312">by</emphasis>
night. Search call shape is FM/CF/ 
<emphasis id="3285EAA6FFEE8A08FD19F9BDFC9EDF20" bold="true" box="[725,795,1564,1603]" pageId="33" pageNumber="312">FM</emphasis>
with a peak F recorded at 96-98 kHz on IshigakÃ¿ima and 92-93 kHz on Iriomotejima.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="004E36B4FFEE8A08FF09F926FDEEDE2E" blockId="33.[195,1819,342,2345]" pageId="33" pageNumber="312">
<emphasis id="3285EAA6FFEE8A08FF09F926FBF7DFCD" bold="true" box="[197,1138,1671,1710]" pageId="33" pageNumber="312">Movements, Home range and Social organization.</emphasis>
The Yaeyama Horseshoe Bat roosts in colonies and females can form maternity colonies with over 1000 individuals while raising young. This species frequently roosts with the Ryukyu Long-fingered Bat 
<emphasis id="3285EAA6FFEE8A08F96BF951FE45DE2E" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="312">(Miniopterusfuscus)</emphasis>
in caves.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="48EB653FFFEE8A08FF0AF8FAF896D1E9" pageId="33" pageNumber="312" type="conservation">
<paragraph id="004E36B4FFEE8A08FF0AF8FAF896D1E9" blockId="33.[195,1819,342,2345]" pageId="33" pageNumber="312">
<emphasis id="3285EAA6FFEE8A08FF0AF8FAFE02DEE1" bold="true" box="[198,391,1883,1922]" pageId="33" pageNumber="312">Status and</emphasis>
Conservation. 
<collectingRegion id="C235F856FFEE8A08FD6DF8FAFD6EDEE1" box="[673,747,1883,1922]" country="Cameroon" name="North" pageId="33" pageNumber="312">Not</collectingRegion>
assessed as a separate species on 
<emphasis id="3285EAA6FFEE8A08FA9EF8FAF9ABDEE1" box="[1362,1582,1883,1922]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="312">TheIUCNed</emphasis>
List, where it is included under the Least Horseshoe Bat 
<emphasis id="3285EAA6FFEE8A08FBE7F82EFA87DED5" box="[1067,1282,1935,1975]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="312">(pusiUus)</emphasis>
as Least Concern. Listed as endangered in the Japanese Red List. Several caves for breeding and hibernating are known to exist on IshigakÃ¿ima Island. However, in recent years, deforestation, roost destruction and tourism activities are creating serious problems for the island bat population. As a consequence, conservation measures need to be established immediately.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="48EB653FFFEE8A08FF0AF73EFC95D040" pageId="33" pageNumber="312" type="reference_group">
